body:
(I don't think this is a duplicate of [1481](https://github.com/AutoMapper/AutoMapper/issues/1481), this is going in the opposite direction.)

After upgrading from 5.0.0 to 5.0.1 (or 5.0.2), I am getting this error:

System.InvalidOperationException: Rewriting child expression from type 'System.Int16' to type 'System.Nullable`1[System.Int16]' is not allowed, because it would change the meaning of the operation. If this is intentional, override 'VisitUnary' and change it to allow this rewrite..

(As a side note, the issues I've run into during Seal have been somewhat difficult to diagnose, e.g. having to comment out mappings until I narrow in on the one that caused the problem. Is it possible to add more diagnostic information like source/dest type/member into the exceptions? I can create a separate issue for this if necessary.)

Here is an example mapping:

```
[TestClass]
public class UnitTest1
{
    static UnitTest1()
    {
        Mapper.Initialize(cfg =>
        {
            cfg.CreateMap<Source, Target>()
                .ForMember(t => t.X, opts => opts.MapFrom(s => s.X > 0 ? s.X : default(short?)));
        });
    }

    [TestMethod]
    public void IncludedMappings()
    {
        var src = new Source
        {
            X = 0
        };

        var dest = Mapper.Map<Source, Target>(src);

        Assert.AreEqual(src.X, dest.X);
    }
}

class Source
{
    public short X { get; set; }
}

class Target
{
    public short? X { get; set; }
}
```

Another interesting aside is that the exception is significantly different if mapping int instead of short:

```
System.InvalidOperationException: The binary operator GreaterThan is not defined for the types 'System.Nullable`1[System.Int32]' and 'System.Int32'..
    at System.Linq.Expressions.Expression.GetUserDefinedBinaryOperatorOrThrow(ExpressionType binaryType, String name, Expression left, Expression right, Boolean liftToNull)
   at System.Linq.Expressions.Expression.GreaterThan(Expression left, Expression right, Boolean liftToNull, MethodInfo method)
```
